{{short description|Greek goddess of hospitality}} {{other uses}} {{Infobox deity |type=Greek |name=Nephele |deity_of=Cloud [[nymph]] |member_of=the Athamantian Royal House |image=Pompeii - Casa dei Vettii - Ixion.jpg |alt= |caption=Punishment of [[Ixion]]: Nephele sitting at [[Mercury (mythology)|Mercury's]] feet. Roman fresco in the [[House of the Vettii]] [[Pompeii]] |other_names= |cult_center= |abode=[[Athamantia]] in [[Boeotia]] |planet= |consort=[[Athamas]] |parents= |siblings= |offspring=[[Phrixus]] and [[Helle (mythology)|Helle]] |predecessor= |successor= |Roman_equivalent= |Etruscan_equivalent= }} In [[Greek mythology]], '''Nephele''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|n|ɛ|f|ə|l|i}}; {{lang-el|Νεφέλη}}, from νέφος ''nephos'' "cloud";<ref>[[Robert S. P. Beekes|R. S. P. Beekes]], ''Etymological Dictionary of Greek'', Brill, 2009, p. 1012.</ref> [[Latin]]ized to ''Nubes'') was a cloud [[nymph]] who figured prominently in the story of [[Phrixus]] and [[Helle (mythology)|Helle]].<ref>[http://www.theoi.com/Text/HyginusAstronomica2.html#20 Hyginus (Mary Grant translation): The Ram], ([[Aries (constellation)|Aries]])</ref> Nephele was also the goddess of hospitality.
== Mythology == Greek myth also has it that Nephele is the cloud whom [[Zeus]] created in the image of [[Hera]] to trick [[Ixion]] to test his integrity after displaying his lust for Hera during a feast as a guest of Zeus. Ixion failed in restraining his lust for Hera, thus fathering the [[Centaur]]s.
Nephele married [[Athamas]], but he divorced her for [[Ino (Greek mythology)|Ino]]. [[Phrixus]] and [[Helle (mythology)|Helle]], the son and daughter of Athamas and Nephele, were hated by their stepmother, Ino. Ino hatched a devious plot to get rid of the twins, roasting all the town's crop seeds so they would not grow. The local farmers, frightened of famine, asked a nearby [[oracle]] for assistance. Ino bribed the men sent to the oracle to lie and tell the others that the oracle required the sacrifice of Phrixus. Before he was killed though, Phrixus and Helle were rescued by a flying golden ram sent by Nephele, their natural mother.
Phrixus and Helle were instructed to not look down to Earth for the duration of their flight. Helle, though, did look down, and fell off the ram into the [[Hellespont]] (which was named after her, meaning ''Sea of Helle'') and drowned, but Phrixus survived all the way to [[Colchis]], where King [[Aeetes]] took him in and treated him kindly, giving Phrixus his daughter, [[Chalciope]], in marriage. In gratitude, Phrixus gave the king the [[Golden Fleece]] of the ram, which Aeetes hung in a tree in his kingdom. The Golden Fleece would later be taken by [[Jason]] and his [[Argonauts]].{{Greek myth (nymph)}}
==See also== * [[Aries (constellation)]]
